<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guess the Bureaucracy:  Week 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<CENTER><H2>Guess the Bureaucracy</H2>
<b>Sponsored by:</b><br>
<a href="/ads/renew/"><img src="/ads/renew.gif" alt="Toward American Renewal"></a>
<P>
<hr width="50%">
</center>
<i>"In a time when information was dear, bureaucracy was a means of organizing it, creating, as it were, a 'priesthood' of civil servants tasked with mastering particular fields of knowledge.  ...In one place in the world--literally--it lives on.  The Federal government.  It lives in practice--in our outmoded models of regulation and the provision of public massistance, in large expanses of the Pentagon, and in the way the government--including the Congress--organizes itself."
</i>
<center><br>--Jeffrey A. Eisenach, <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-july/ac795je.html">"An Obsolete Federal Government"</a>
</center>

<hr width="30%"><P>
<br>
This week's Town Hall Spotlight provides you with the chance to learn a little bit about these "priesthoods"--government bureaucracies--that run on your hard earned money, and win a Town Hall t-shirt in the process.  
<ol>
<li>Read the hints next to each picture.  
<li>Click on the picture to view a larger image.  
<li>Fill in your guess in the box next to each picture.
<li>Submit the form.  One lucky person will be chosen randomly from among those who guess every agency correctly to win a Town Hall T-shirt!
<li>Check back next week, when we'll label and link to each bureacracy and relevant articles from Town Hall Citizen Organizations.   
<li>More bureaucracies will be featured in next week's Spotlight.
</ol>
<form method="POST" action="/townhall/scripts/form-handler.cgi">
<br>
<input name="01name" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> Name<br>        
<input name="02address" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> Address<br>
<input name="03city" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> City<br>
<input name="04state" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> State or Country    <br>
<input name="05zip" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> ZIP Code<br>
<SELECT name="08T-size"> 
<OPTION> L
<OPTION> XL
</select> Preferred T-Shirt Size
<P>
<input name="06e-mail address" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> E-mail address<br>
<input name="07how found TH" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> How did you hear about Town Hall?

<P>
<b>NOTE:</b> Only fully completed forms will be eligible to win the T-shirt. <b>Good luck!</b>
<hr><P>
<br>
<A HREF="1.jpg"><IMG SRC="1.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="1" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul><li>None of this bureacracy's employees stayed at home during the last shutdown; not because there were no "non-essential" employees, but because its fiscal 1996 appropriation bill had already been approved.
<li>Had budgeted $13 billion in fiscal 1996 ($434 billion over the next 5 years) for promotion of profitable US companies in foreign markets.  That's right:  your tax dollars are being spent to advertise for successful corporations.  Rep. Dick Armey called this "Coporate welfare of the worst kind"
<li>Its budget increase 881 percent between 1965 and 1995.
</ul>
<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="2.jpg"><IMG SRC="2.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="2" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul><li>Since its creation in 1979, this bureaucracy's budget has more than doubled, to over $31 billion per year.  The vast majority of this money goes to fund technical assistance, clearinghouses, information, and specific (and often unpopular) programs, rather than to direct improvement of its claimed area of oversight.
<li>89% of its civilian staff (4,400 persons) was labeled "non-essential."</ul>


<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="3.jpg"><IMG SRC="3.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="3" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul><li>It is the nation's oldest federal regulatory agency. 
<li>It has a current annual budget of approximately $5 billion.
<li>It controls how firms move into and out of the regulated sector, and ensures that the rates charged by those firms were "just and reasonable."  Major reforms in the early 1980s reduced the control of this agency over its area of oversight, and increased competition and lowered prices in the process.
</ul>



</ul>
<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="4.jpg"><IMG SRC="4.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="4" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul><li>67% of its civilian staff (approximately 25,100 people) was labeled "non-essential" during the November shut-down.
<li>It is "a loose collection of more than 100 programs delivering services to about 1,000 customer bases," according to its own Inspector General.
<li>Its annual budget is approximately $3.6 billion.
</ul>

<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="5.jpg"><IMG SRC="5.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="5" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul><li>This building was constructed between 1871 and 1888 to house the burgeoning Departments of State, War and Navy (two of which now have their own buildings as large as or larger than this one).  It now houses assistants to the President.
<li>It has an excellent view of the White House.</ul>

<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="6.jpg"><IMG SRC="6.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="6" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul><li>This bureaucracy was created by Jimmy Carter in 1977.
<li>Weapons production and environmental cleanup, rather than its original area of oversight, now dominate its budget.
<li>Operates the Naval Petroleum Reserve, a series of oil fields set aside by Presidents Taft and Wilson to assure fuel for the Navy as it converted from coal to oil.
<li>Has a prefunded payroll, running through December, which prevented any of its staffers from being furloughed in November.
</ul>


<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="7.jpg"><IMG SRC="7.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="7" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul><li>While responsible for collecting 98 percent of the government's revenues--currently $1.25 trillion annually--this agency has not kept its own books and records with the same degree of accuracy it expects of citizens. 
<li>Its financial systems are outdated and unreliable, according to the GAO.
<li>Between 1990 and 1994, funds due to but not collected by this agency rose from $87 billion to $156 billion.
<li>Its very existence makes every American dread April 15th.
</ul><P><P>

<br>

<center>
Comments about these bureaucracies or this game?
