<blockquote>
<center><h3>Small Business <font color="#ff0000"><i>Hill Alert</font></i></h3><p>
<b>
Publication Notices &amp; Issue Updates
</b>
<P>
SEPTEMBER 26, 1996<p>
ISSUE NO. 21<p>
<hr>
<P>
<b>
Update on a Few Issues<BR>
</b>
</center>
<P>
First, a quick thank you for those of you who weighed in to help
us defeat the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC), and the Employment
Non-Discrimination Act (ENDA).  As you know, both would have placed
new regulatory burdens on business.<BR>
<P>
<B>CWC</B> -- In the end, the Senate did not have enough votes
to pass the CWC so supporters decided to pull it from consideration
for ratification.  What this means is that our CWC victory is
temporary.  The bad news is that the CWC will probably rear its
ugly head next year.<BR>
<P>
<B>ENDA</B> -- The same can be said for ENDA.  While ENDA was
defeated in the Senate by only one vote, the legislation will
continue to come before the Congress as long as Ted Kennedy remains
a member of the United States Senate.  Stay tuned and prepared.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Immigration </B>-- Legislation to curb illegal immigration
will be voted on soon.  We remain strongly opposed to the voluntary
employee verification program due to the burden it will place
on employers and employees alike.  The &quot;voluntary&quot; system
will most definitely become mandatory in the future.  SBSC believes
that the new system is flawed in that it will be riddled with
errors thus delaying the hiring process.  Please call SBSC to
receive more information so you can contact your member of Congress
with your concerns.
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT COLOR=#000000>Small Business Issues and the '96
Elections<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<I><B><FONT COLOR=#000000>Entrepreneurs and Elections</FONT></B></I><FONT COLOR=#000000>
-- The '96 elections gives small business owners the opportunity
to determine where incumbent members of Congress and their challengers
stand on key issues  important to the small business/entrepreneurial
sector of the economy.  The Small Business Survival (SBS) Foundation
has written a book called &quot;Entrepreneurs and Elections '96
-- A Candidates Guide to Key Small Business Issues.&quot;  Please
call SBSC if you would like to receive a copy.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT COLOR=#000000>Ratings of the 104th Congress </FONT></B></I><FONT COLOR=#000000>--
Call today to get a copy of <I>SBSC's Ratings of the 104th</I>
<I>Congress.</I>  Using votes on key small business issues during
the 104th Congress, SBSC has rated each member of the U.S. House
and Senate so you can determine if your representatives' rhetoric
matches their voting record.  To receive the scores of your Congressman
or Senators, please call SBSC today.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT COLOR=#000000>SBSC Says Thank You to the 104th
Congress<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>On Wednesday, September 25, SBSC joined a
coalition of taxpayer, consumer and senior organizations to express
their thanks to the 104th Congress.  The &quot;Salute to the 104th
Congress&quot; was held on Capitol Hill, and SBSC President Karen
Kerrigan had the opportunity to thank members of Congress -- both
individually and collectively -- for their bold steps to help
protect entrepreneurs and encourage small business start-ups.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>&quot;Looking back at the last two years,
the 104th Congress passed historic measures to help small business
and promote entrepreneurship,&quot; said Kerrigan.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Kerrigan presented a special award to Speaker
Newt Gingrich at the ceremony, and 60 members of Congress who
scored 80% or higher on SBSC's ratings received a special tribute
and photo-op with the Speaker's award.  Over 600 people attended
the event.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>SBSC praised Republican-led reforms signed
by the President.  SBSC also thanked Congress for passing broad,
comprehensive tax and regulatory reforms supported by small business,
but vetoed by the President.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>&quot;While we are pleased that President
Clinton signed several of the initiatives target to help small
businesses, unfortunately he vetoed or stood in the way of other
reform priorities recommended by his own White House Conference
on Small Business,&quot; added Kerrigan.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>SBSC applauded the Congress for its passage
of health insurance reforms to help small business including the
phasing-in of deductibility to 80%, and passing Medical Savings
Accounts.  In addition, regulators are now more accountable to
small businesses because Congress put teeth into Regulatory Flexibility.
 Regulators must also publish their rules and regulations in &quot;Plain
English&quot; and Congress can now conduct a final review of regulations
and vote to reject them.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>President  Clinton vetoed the following small
business initiatives:  capital gains tax reduction, estate tax
reform, legal reform, the TEAM Act and a balanced budget.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>&quot;Most importantly, the 104th Congress
began to chip away at the old status quo through its cuts in wasteful
government spending to balance the budget,&quot; said Kerrigan.</FONT>
<p><br>
</blockquote>
