<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<p>
<blockquote>
<center><h3>Small Business <font color="#ff0000"><i>Hill Alert</font></i></h3><p>
<P>
<b>
Convention Address; New publications:
<p>
Ratings of the 104th Congress, Time to Overhaul the NLRB
</b>
<p>
 August  28, 1996<p>
Issue No. 19<BR>
<hr>
<P>
 <B>Less Government, Less Taxes, More Freedom<BR>
</B>
</center>
<P>
1994 saw a record number of entrepreneurs and successful small
business people elected to Congress.  
<P>
 With 32 of 86 Congressional freshman former (or current) small
business owners heralding the economic advantages of small business
growth, the 104th Congress shifted from an anti-business to a
pro-entrepreneur agenda.   See Congress Becoming More Friendly
to Small Business.
<P>
Small-business Congress members have helped lawmakers focus on
fiscal and tax policies that aid small businesses in creating
new job opportunities for Americans.   
<P>
According to a 1995 March U.S. News &amp; World Report, there
are now 191 representatives who used to work in business-related
occupations, compared with 170 who worked in law.  
<P>
 This week <I>Small Business Hill Alert </I>highlights a speech
by small business woman, Sue Wittig, a candidate for New York's
 26th congressional district.   Ms. Wittig's speech typifies SBSC's
freemarket, limited government ideology. 
<P>
Sue Wittig's address was delivered to GOP delegates at the Republican
convention on August 12th, 1996.  <BR>
<P>
<I>My name is Sue Wittig, and I'm running for Congress.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>I'm a small business woman from Saugerties, New York.  Along
with my husband, I run a paint and wallpaper store, a family business
that was started by my Dad over thirty years ago...<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>Together with my Mom, [my Dad] built a business - and a family.
 And [he] taught me the value of both.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>We need representatives who understand the value of families...
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>We need representatives who understand the marketplace.  It
is the small businesses of Newburgh, Kingston, Ithaca, and Owego
who are creating tomorrow's jobs.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>We need representatives who understand limited government.
 Congress was designed to be a citizen Legislature, for people
to ..., serve their community and country, and</I> <B>go back
home</B><I>.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>...From the small business owners...and the mothers and fathers
struggling to pay their taxes ....<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>The message is simple: <B>less government, less taxes, more
freedom.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</B></I>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Time to Overhaul the NLRB <BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
The Small Business Survival (SBS) Foundation released a new <I><B>Small
Business Reg Watch</B></I>  documenting the bias of the National
Labor Relations Board (NLRB) and its interpretation of labor law.
 The report also outlines reform measures to move  labor law and
the NLRB into the 21st century.
<P>
According to the study entitled &quot;Time to Overhaul Labor Law
and the NLRB,&quot; the NLRB has taken judicial activism to the
extreme - blatant political NLRB decisions have been consistently
reversed by the courts who hear such cases.  In addition, current
NLRB Chairman William Gould has publicly stated his support or
opposition to various pieces of legislation before Congress -
an act that is unprecedented for what is supposed to be an impartial
arbritor of labor law.
<P>
For a copy of the study, call SBS Foundation at 1-800-223-7526
<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Congress Becoming More Friendly to Small Business<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
The 104th Congress has improved markedly over the previous Congress
in terms of its votes on legislation to help small business and
enhance entrepreneurship. 
<P>
 &quot;Especially during its first term, the 104th Congress was
enthusiastically pro-entrepreneur.  Tax and regulatory relief
legislation, combined with proposals to cut the size and scope
of government all comprise the small business agenda,&quot; said
SBSC President Karen Kerrigan.
<P>
Kerrigan continued, &quot;The change in Congress marked a tremendous
shift in the direction of the small business agenda on Capitol
Hill.  Rather than small business being on the defensive, we were
able to consistently support legislation being considered on the
floor of both Houses.&quot;
<P>
 However, while Congress passed an unprecedented level of legislation
supported by small businesses and entrepreneurs, these measures
were largely vetoed by President Clinton.
<P>
&quot;Unfortunately, the bulk of legislation aimed towards the
growth and survival of small business was rejected by the President,&quot;
Kerrigan noted.
<P>
At the time of the release of SBSC's <I>Ratings of the 104th Congress</I>,
Congress was preparing to send the minimum wage hike amendment
to the President's desk for approval. 
<P>
The ratings were completed prior to the wage hike vote.  Its consideration
would have proven damaging for many members ratings.
<P>
For a copy of the ratings, contact SBSC at 800-223-7526.
<p><br>
</blockquote>
