<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hill Alert: Senators and Small Business advocates Grade Clinton</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<center>
<h3>Small Business <font color="FF0000"><i>Hill Alert</i></h3></font>
<p>
<i>June  6, 1996 ,Issue
No. 15<BR></i>
<P>
<B>U.S. Senators and Small Business Advocates &quot;Grade&quot;
Clinton on WHCSB Recommendations</B>
<P>
<hr>
<p>
<B>  Small Business Survival Foundation Releases Study Ranking<BR>
Entrepreneurship Across the U.S.<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>  <I><FONT SIZE=4>Calls to Action</FONT></I> : Immigration
Bill Nears Reconciliation Date;<BR> Starting Wage Amendment in Senate
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<hr>
<p>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>President Clinton Receives Unsatisfactory
Marks from Small Business Advocates<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>
<FONT SIZE=2>The Small Business Survival Committee (SBSC) participated
in a press conference on June 5 to help unveil a &quot;report
card&quot; on President Clinton's record on implementing recommendations
from the June 1995 White House Conference on Small Business. 
Senator Kit Bond (R-MO), Chairman of the Senate Small Business
Committee hosted the event.  Also joining the press conference
were Senators Paul Coverdell (R-GA), Kay Bailey Hutchison (R-TX),
Don Nickles (R-OK), Bill Frist (R-TN), Conrad Burns (R-MT), Larry
Pressler (R-SD) and representatives from small business groups.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B>President Bill Clinton</B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Report Card</B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>on the Small Business Agenda<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
<PRE>
<B>SMALL BUSINESS AGENDA                GRADE</B>
<P>
Balanced Budget                          F
<P>
Regulatory Flexibility Act               Incomplete
<P>
Regulatory Reform                        F
<P>
Paperwork Reduction                      D
<P>
OSHA Reform                              F
<P>
Product Liability                        F
<P>
Superfund Reform                         D
<P>
Property Rights                          D
<P>
Independent Contractor                   C
<P>
Estate Tax Reform                        F
<P>
Health Insurance for the Self-Employed   F
<P>
Capital Gains (<B>Tax Reduction</B>)            F
<P>
Employer-employee Cooperation (TEAM Act) D
<P>
Davis-Bacon Repeal                       D
<P>
Increased Expensing                      F<BR>
<P>
<B>OVERALL GPA                              D-<BR>
</B>
</PRE>
<P>
At the June 5 press conference, SBSC President Karen Kerrigan
stated, &quot;The President has been given ample opportunity to
support the small business agenda...it is clear that he continues
to embrace an economic model that puts government at the center
of the economy, rather than the entrepreneur.&quot;<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Study Looks at Entrepreneur Climate Across the United
States<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
Marking the start of National Small Business Week, the Small Business
Survival Foundation formally released a report that provides a
measure of government-related costs affecting the business decisions
of investors, entrepreneurs, and businesses across the United
States.  The report, the <B>Small Business Survival Index</B>,
combines nine major costs (whether rates, ratios, or indexes)
levied on small businesses and entrepreneurs into one comparative
index number.  <BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B>*** CALL TO ACTION ***<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B> Reconciliation of Immigration Bills by Mid-June <BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
 All businesses <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT> including
small businesses <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT> face additional
regulations through the proposed adoption of the employment verification
measure.  It passed in both the House and Senate versions of the
immigration proposals. San Diego employers currently using a toll-free
verification system similar to House measure report that the system
can take up to &quot;three calls, several minutes, and sometimes
several days to verify a Social Security number...&quot;  At this
point, the verification system will be voluntary, but SBSC believes
it will eventually become mandatory.
<P>
SBSC's position:  The verification system does not recognize the
administrative and regulatory burdens associated with operating
a business.  Illegal immigrants who show remarkable deftness at
skirting U.S. laws will continue to do so even under the system.
 Hence, the law-abiding employer using the proposed system (and
American citizens) will be the only persons &quot;caught&quot;
by this intrusive system.
<P>
       <B> Time still exists to make your voices heard</B>.  Call
your Representatives and Senators, tell them to say no to additional
regulations  -- &quot;voluntary&quot; or not.<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Starting Wage Proposal in the Senate <BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
The Senate will soon offer their version of the starting wage
bill.  It is expected to closely parallel the House proposal and
increase the starting wage by $0.90 by 1997.  The following provisions
have been added: (1) tipped employees would have the federal cash
wage frozen at $2.13 per hour, instead of 50 percent of the current
federal starting wage and (2) new hires would be paid an &quot;opportunity
wage&quot; during their first 90 calendar days of employment.
 
<P>
It is probable that Senator Kennedy will offer an amendment to
strip these provisions - thereby attempting to force a straight
starting wage bill with the $0.90 increase.  
<P>
<B>Small business owners still have time to weigh-in with the
Senators.   </B>Let them know that you oppose any increase in
the starting wage, but if an increase is unavoidable, then include
the small-business provisions passed by the House.  <U>Most importantly,
tell your Senators not to support any amendment that strips the
tip credit or the opportunity wage language.<BR>
<BR>
</U>
<center>| <a href="/sbsc/">SBSC Home</a> | <a href="/sbsc/i-ha.html"><i>Hill Alerts</i> Index</a> |</center>
<p><br>
